Here's a basic C++ function that takes a reference to a `std::string` containing markdown formatted text and returns a `std::string` containing HTML formatted text:

```cpp
#include <string>
#include <regex>

std::string markdownToHtml(const std::string& markdown) {
    std::string html = markdown;

    // Headers
    std::regex headerRegex("^(#+)\\s*(.+?)$");
    html = std::regex_replace(html, headerRegex, "<h$1>$2</h$1>");

    // Bold
    std::regex boldRegex("\\*\\*(.+?)\\*\\*");
    html = std::regex_replace(html, boldRegex, "<strong>$1</strong>");

    // Italic
    std::regex italicRegex("\\*(.+?)\\*");
    html = std::regex_replace(html, italicRegex, "<em>$1</em>");

    // Links
    std::regex linkRegex("\\[(.+?)\\]\\((.+?)\\)");
    html = std::regex_replace(html, linkRegex, "<a href=\"$2\">$1</a>");

    // Paragraphs
    std::regex paragraphRegex("(^|\\n)([^\\n]+)(\\n|$)");
    html = std::regex_replace(html, paragraphRegex, "$1<p>$2</p>$3");

    // Line breaks
    std::regex lineBreakRegex("\\n");
    html = std::regex_replace(html, lineBreakRegex, "<br>");

    return html;
}
```

This function uses regular expressions to convert various markdown elements to their corresponding HTML tags:

1. Headers: The function matches markdown headers (e.g., `# Header 1`, `## Header 2`) and replaces them with the appropriate HTML header tags (`<h1>`, `<h2>`, etc.).

2. Bold: The function matches text surrounded by double asterisks (`**bold text**`) and replaces it with the HTML `<strong>` tag.

3. Italic: The function matches text surrounded by single asterisks (`*italic text*`) and replaces it with the HTML `<em>` tag.

4. Links: The function matches markdown links (`[link text](url)`) and replaces them with the HTML `<a>` tag.

5. Paragraphs: The function matches paragraphs (text separated by blank lines) and wraps them with the HTML `<p>` tag.

6. Line breaks: The function replaces newline characters (`\n`) with the HTML `<br>` tag.

Please note that this is a basic implementation and may not cover all markdown syntax elements. You can extend the function to handle additional markdown features as needed.

Also, keep in mind that this implementation uses the C++11 regex library (`<regex>`). Make sure your compiler supports C++11 or later to use this code.

